@section Alt and ESC on non-X11 terminals

@cindex Alt key
@cindex ESC key
@cindex terminal Alt

On a character terminal (without X11), @kbd{Alt-X} is entered by pressing
@key{ESC} then @kbd{X}.  A bare @key{ESC} is entered by pressing
@key{ESC} followed by @key{Return}.  (Documented since v1.4.)

@section Special windows

@cindex windows
@cindex special windows

This section describes the special-purpose windows in xwpe.  All are
read-only unless otherwise noted.  (Documented since v1.4.)

@subsection The Find Window

@cindex Find Window

The Find Window lists all directories containing files that match the
search criteria from @samp{File @result{} Find}.  Press @key{Return}
or @kbd{Alt-S} to open a file manager for the selected directory
showing the matching files.  Press @key{ESC} to close the window.

@subsection The Grep Window

@cindex Grep Window

The Grep Window lists all files containing strings that match the
search criteria from @samp{File @result{} Grep}.  Press @key{Return}
or @kbd{Alt-S} to open the marked file for editing; the cursor jumps
to the first occurrence.  Press @key{ESC} to close the window.

@subsection The Message Window

@cindex Message Window

Compiler and linker errors are listed in the Message Window (read-only).
Select an error by moving with cursor keys and pressing @key{Return},
or click with the mouse.  The source file is switched to the current
window (if not already loaded, it is opened in a new window) and the
cursor jumps to the position indicated by the compiler.
(Detail from German manpage.)

@subsection The Project Window

@cindex Project Window

Displays all files in the project.  @kbd{Alt-A} or @key{Insert} opens
the window in add-status to add a file.  @kbd{Alt-E} or @key{Return}
edits an entry.  @kbd{Alt-D} or @key{Delete} deletes an item (only
available when the Project Window is open).
(Detail from German manpage.)  Press @kbd{Alt-E} or @key{Return} to edit an entry,
@kbd{Alt-D} or @key{Delete} to remove an entry, @kbd{Alt-O} to open
project options, @key{ESC} to close.

@subsection The Variable Window

@cindex Variable Window

The Variable Window (opened from Project Options) displays project
variables.  Press @kbd{Alt-A} or @key{Insert} to add, @kbd{Alt-E}
or @key{Return} to edit, @kbd{Alt-D} or @key{Delete} to remove,
@key{ESC} to close.  (Documented since v1.4.)

@subsection The Install Window

@cindex Install Window

The Install Window (opened from Project Options) displays and edits
the commands executed by the @samp{install} target.  Press @kbd{Alt-A}
or @key{Insert} to add, @kbd{Alt-E} or @key{Return} to edit,
@kbd{Alt-D} or @key{Delete} to remove, @key{ESC} to close.
(Documented since v1.4.)

@subsection The Watch Window

@cindex Watch Window

The Watch Window shows the values of variables selected via the watch
function (@pxref{Debugging}).  Use cursor keys and the search function
to navigate.  Press @key{Return} to edit a selected variable, or to
add a new one if the last line is selected.  Press @key{Insert} to
insert a new entry; @key{Delete} to remove one.  If a variable is not
found in the current scope, a warning is displayed.

@subsection The Stack Window

@cindex Stack Window

The Stack Window shows the program call stack (read-only).  Navigate
with cursor keys; press @key{Return} to jump to a stack frame in the
source.  The stack can be examined when a signal is caught by the
program.

@section The Execution Manager

@cindex Execution Manager

The Execution Manager (@samp{File @result{} Execute}) selects and runs
executable files and shell scripts.  Only files with the execute permission
are shown in the Files list.  (Documented since v1.4.)

