@section Function Index

@cindex Function Index
@cindex man pages
@cindex MANPATH

The Function Index (@samp{Help @result{} Function Index} or @kbd{Ctrl-F1})
creates a list of all manual pages found via the @env{MANPATH} environment
variable.  The index is divided into sections.
(Documented since v1.4.)

@table @strong
@item User Commands
Section 1 man pages.
@item System Calls
C system call functions (section 2).
@item C Library Functions
C library functions (section 3).
@item Devices & Network Interfaces
Section 4.
@item File Formats
Section 5.
@item Games & Demos
Section 6.
@item Environments, Tables and TROFF Macros
Section 7.
@item Maintenance Commands
System administration commands (section 8).
@end table

Select a section to see a list of available man pages.  Select a page
by pressing @key{Return} or clicking on the name.  Man pages are
read-only documents but can serve as sources for editing commands.

A manual page can also be viewed by name via @samp{Help @result{}
Function} (@kbd{Alt-H T}).

@section C programming utilities

@cindex C programming
@cindex show definition
@cindex matching bracket
@cindex beautify

For C and C++ source files, xwpe provides several programming aids
accessed from the @samp{Run} menu or via @kbd{Ctrl-O} chords.
(Documented since v1.4.)

@subsection Show Definition (@kbd{Ctrl-O S})

Jump to the definition of a C expression.  xwpe opens the file
containing the definition and highlights it.  Searchable definitions
include: @code{struct}, @code{union}, @code{class}, @code{typedef},
preprocessor @code{#define}, @code{extern} variables, and functions.

If a project is defined, all project files are scanned.  All
@code{#include}d files are scanned recursively, following the
System-Include-Path defined in @samp{Options @result{} Programming}.

If the name has multiple definitions (e.g.@: both a @code{struct} and
an @code{extern} variable), use @kbd{Ctrl-O N} (Show Next Definition)
to cycle through them.

@subsection Matching Bracket (@kbd{Ctrl-O K})

If the cursor is on a bracket, xwpe finds the matching opening or
closing bracket and moves the cursor to it.  If the cursor is not on a
bracket, xwpe moves to the next opening bracket.  Recognised bracket
pairs: @code{@{@}}, @code{[]}, and @code{()}.

@subsection Beautify (@kbd{Ctrl-O B})

Reformat C source code by re-indenting all blocks according to their
nesting depth.  The indentation step size is taken from the auto-indent
setting in @samp{Options @result{} Editor}.

@section Project options dialog

@cindex project options

The project options dialog (@samp{Project @result{} Options},
@kbd{Alt-P O}) provides the following fields.
(Documented since v1.4.)

@table @strong
@item Compiler
The path to the compiler.
@item Compiler-Options
Flags passed to the compiler.
@item Loader-Options
Flags passed to the linker.
@item Executable-Name
The name of the resulting executable (default: @code{a.out}).
@item Store Objects in Library
If a filename is entered, all object files are stored in this library,
which is then used automatically for linking.
@item Compiler-Style
@code{GNU} (default) or @code{Other} (custom message-string).
@item Variables ...
Opens the Variable Window to define and manage project variables.
@item Install ...
Opens the Install Window to define and manage install commands.
@item Save
Save the project file.
@item Save As
Save the project file under a new name.
@item CANCEL
Close without saving.
@end table
